<p style="font-weight: bold;">Was the first urban planner a photographer? </p>

<p> Although the SF Urban Film Fest maybe the first urban planning film festival, images have always inspired urban planning.  The heart-wrenching photography of Jacob Riis in his seminal book “How The Other Half Lives” chronicled the lives of poor immigrants in the tenements of New York City’s Lower East Side in the early 20th century.  His photographs inspired the Tenement Housing Movement who in turn pushed New York City to enact the nation’s first laws regulating housing conditions.  Visual activism is often over shadowed by discussions of the physical environment, grass-roots organizing, and legislative change in lessons of urban history.  At the SF Urban Film Fest, we bring visual storytelling to the forefront in the creation of our urban future. </p>

