<p style="font-weight: bold;">What is an urban planning film festival? </p>

<p> At the SF Urban Film Fest, we screen films showing how the built environment effects society - and vice versa - in cities.  These urban planning films highlight the hard work and commitment of visionary leaders, regular citizens, and government forging change in cities.  The emerging urban planning film genre shares common ground with documentaries from the environmental and global social justice movements.  The most notable of these films is the Academy Award winning An Inconvenient Truth (2006, USA) which utilized the star power of former U.S. Vice President Al Gore and transformed an ivory tower scientific debate into a global popular discourse about climate change.</p>

<p>What differentiates the SF Urban Film Fest from other film festivals is our focus on connecting the themes of the films to campaigns actively being pursued by governmental and non-profit organizations working for change in San Francisco.  We want to prove that a good film can inspire you to join others in making San Francisco a better place to live. </p>

</div>


