<p style="font-weight: bold;">SF Urban Asks Urban Planner/Artist James Rojas: “How do you sustain public engagement in the urban planning process?” </p>

<p style="font-weight: bold;">James: </p>
	<p> “Creativity.  Urban planners need to capture the emotional and experiential aspects of city life in their methods and tools.  Currently, the outreach tools - lists, dots on a map, stakeholder groups - are too abstract.  The creative process on the other hand is one of passion, discovery, and self-satisfaction.  Artists, filmmakers, and writers are driven by the creative process which allows them to imagine, investigate, construct, and reflect. </p>

<p style="font-weight: bold;">SF Urban: </p>
	<p> How does your idea about creativity translate to public participation in urban planning?</p>
 
<p style="font-weight: bold;">James: </p>
	<p> The participant becomes the artist, writer, or filmmaker.  Let the public create narratives about how they experience urban life.  Let them tell stories, visualize their ideal environments, document how they experience the physical world, share their ideas with others, and ultimately have their ideas validated.</p>
 
<p style="font-weight: bold;">SF Urban: </p>
	<p> That kind of work has no end. 
 
<p style="font-weight: bold;">James: </p>
	<p> Exactly. The city is an artist that is always producing new work to solve problems and desires.  </p>

